## EXIT SESSION CHECKLIST

**BEFORE starting exit: always ask Ryan if he is done.**
Never run the exit checklist unless Ryan explicitly says he is done, wrapping up, or leaving.
Do not assume the session is over because a task was completed.

Run this before ending any conversation where meaningful work was done.

### PRE-CLOSE SAFETY CHECK (run even if Ryan forgets to ask for full exit)

If the conversation appears to be ending and Ryan has not explicitly requested the full exit checklist:
- Run a brief critical check and report it before final sign-off:
  1. Any unlogged test outcome that should be written to docs
  2. Any unresolved blocker that could cause next-session confusion
  3. Any required next-session one-time action that must be surfaced now
- Keep this lightweight (3 bullets max), then ask Ryan if he wants full exit protocol.
- Do NOT run commits/push or full exit sequence unless Ryan explicitly confirms he is done.

### DAILY EXECUTION CLOSEOUT (run whenever meaningful work happened)

Before final sign-off for the session, update `docs/WEEKLY_EXECUTION_TRACKER.md`:
- Planned hours vs actual hours for today
- Drift reason and carry-forward item
- Tasks planned vs tasks done for today
- Confidence of evidence used (logged/reported/inferred)

If today is Saturday:
- Complete weekly quick audit block in tracker
- Write next-week corrective actions
- Set next week's daily objectives before ending the session

If today is the last Saturday of the month:
- Run the monthly deep audit block in tracker
- Record verdict and recovery actions in `docs/ACCOUNTABILITY_AUDIT_LOG.md`
- State timeline impact on full-time target (on track/slight risk/off track)

**Always tell Ryan to start a NEW chat next session — never continue this one.**
Say this explicitly at the end of every exit:
"Start a fresh chat next time — don't continue this one. The rules and project files
will reload everything automatically. A fresh chat thinks faster and makes fewer mistakes."

Reason: long conversations reduce the model's available thinking space, leading to slower
responses and subtle errors. PROJECT_CONTEXT.md, PATCH_NOTES.md, and the rules ensure
no context is lost between sessions.

1. **Deliver a session summary to Ryan**
   Before touching any files, give a plain-English recap of what was accomplished:

   "Here's what we got done today:
   - [Accomplishment 1]
   - [Accomplishment 2]
   - [Accomplishment 3 if applicable]
   [One sentence on anything left unfinished, if relevant.]"

   Keep it brief — 3–5 bullets max. This is for Ryan, not for documentation.

2. **Update PATCH_NOTES.md**
   Log what was accomplished, any decisions made, and any new open items.

2b. **Record tomorrow schedule + carry-forward in PATCH_NOTES.md (always)**
   At the end of every meaningful session, add a short block Ryan can execute tomorrow:
   - **Tomorrow scheduled task:** one primary task tied to day theme
   - **Carry-forward from today:** unfinished item(s), if any
   - **Work-ahead status:** worked ahead / on-plan / behind
   - **Tomorrow sync tasks:** any required setup/checklist items first
   Rule: if work was completed ahead of schedule, explicitly say what tomorrow can skip.
   Rule: if behind schedule, explicitly state the catch-up target for tomorrow.

2c. **Code map hygiene (when architecture changed)**
   If enter checklist **step 10** (code-doc sync) was not run during the session but routing, stores, or integrations were materially changed, either run **"Run code-doc sync."** now or add a carry-forward line in PATCH_NOTES: `CODEBASE_MAP.md` needs update.

2a. **Amber notes maintenance (if Amber work happened this session)**
   If an Amber test session occurred, or Amber action items were completed:
   - Update `docs/AMBER_TEST_HISTORY.md` with date, delivery path, pass/fail, and key feedback.
   - Update `docs/TONIGHT_AMBER_TEST_RESULTS.md` with final outcomes and next actions.
   - Remove or delete Amber one-time prep docs only when they are fully completed and their important details are already captured in history/results files.
   - If new Amber follow-up tests are needed, create the next test note/checklist in `docs/` before ending the session.

3. **Update PROJECT_CONTEXT.md**
   If any decisions changed the project direction, phase status, or known flags — update it.

3a. **Update ROADMAP_TIMELINE.md (milestone sessions only)**
   If a phase milestone was completed this session (all checklist items for a phase marked done):
   - Mark the phase complete in Section C and record the actual completion date.
   - Update the Pace Check table in the header with the actual date and revised verdict.
   - Update Section A "Today" column to reflect the new state.
   - Note any items that slipped to the next phase.
   If no milestone was hit this session, skip this step.

3b. **Update forecasting docs (milestone sessions only)**
   If a phase milestone was completed this session:
   - Update `docs/ESTIMATION_RETROSPECTIVE.md` with safe target, actual date, and delta (days early/late).
   - Score capability factors (Cursor assist effectiveness + Ryan familiarity + scope clarity + unknowns + test friction).
   - Update `docs/FORECAST_BASELINES.md` only if evidence supports a multiplier change.
   If no milestone was hit this session, skip this step.

4. **Run linter before committing**
   Run: `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; npx expo lint`
   If errors appear, fix them before committing. Never push broken code to GitHub.
   If warnings only (no errors), note them but proceed.

5. **Flag new npm packages if any were installed**
   If any `npm install` commands were run this session, tell Ryan:
   "New packages were added. If you open this project on another device,
   run: npm install — in the terminal first."

6. **Commit and push to GitHub**
   Run git status to confirm what changed, then:
   - `cd "c:\App Development\sticker-quest"; git add .`
   - Commit with a clear plain-English summary message
   - `git push origin main`
   Tell Ryan: "Everything is saved to GitHub. Your work is backed up."
   If push fails, explain the problem plainly and give a simple fix.

7. **Next session options — prioritized**
   Do not just say "Your next move." Instead, give Ryan a short prioritized menu
   of 2–4 options based on:
   - Current phase and what's blocking progress
   - Whether a time-sensitive promo (Claude 2x, etc.) is active or expiring soon
   - Whether we're currently in peak or off-peak hours
   - What's sitting in PENDING_SPRINTS.md
   - Any open critical flags in PROJECT_CONTEXT.md

   Format it like this:

   **Next Session — Your Options (in my recommended order):**
   1. [URGENT if applicable] [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   2. [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   3. [Option name] — [1-sentence reason why] | ⏱ ~X min (reliable/may vary)
   *(Optional) Off-peak bonus: [Name of Claude Pro sprint to run] — best time: [when]*

   Time estimate rules:
   - Content tasks (Claude Pro sprints, JSON merges): label as "reliable" — these are predictable
   - Code tasks (building features, fixing bugs): label as "may vary" — unexpected issues are normal
   - Never give a code estimate without a "may vary" warning
   - If a code task has a known hidden risk (e.g., touching a stub that may cascade), flag it explicitly

   Always give a recommended order. Never just list options without a preference.
   Always factor in deadlines and promo windows when ranking.

8. **Flag anything time-sensitive**
   If something needs to happen before a deadline (e.g., March 27 Claude Pro sprint),
   say so explicitly at the end of the session.

